AI Data Exfiltration Malware Detector – Backend Prototype
Overview

This repository contains an initial backend prototype developed independently as part of the Curtin University Capstone project:
AI-Driven Detection of Data-Exfiltration Malware on Mobile Devices

The purpose of this repository is to demonstrate the early backend architecture, API design, and detection logic used for analysing suspicious behaviour from mobile devices.
This repository was created separately from the official project repository to document individual development progress and time spent working on the backend system.

Official team repository (Bitbucket):
https://bitbucket.org/curtincomputingprojects/bentley-sem-2-group-12/src/main/ 

Personal development repository (this repo):
https://github.com/gitvihanga/ai-data-exfiltration-detector

System Architecture
The backend is implemented using FastAPI, a high-performance Python web framework suitable for building machine-learning APIs and scalable services.
The prototype backend provides a simple API that receives behavioural indicators from a mobile device and classifies the activity as Safe or Suspicious.

Architecture overview:

Mobile Client (Android App)
↓
FastAPI Backend
↓
Detection Engine (Python logic)
↓
Prediction + Confidence Score

The backend exposes endpoints that can later be integrated with the Android client application.

Project Structure
backend
│
├── app
│   ├── main.py        # FastAPI application and API endpoints
│   ├── detector.py    # Detection logic for suspicious behaviour
│   └── schemas.py     # Request and response data models
│
└── requirements.txt   # Python dependencies

Backend Components
main.py

Defines the FastAPI application and API routes.

Endpoints:

GET /health
Returns backend status.

POST /analyze
Receives behavioural data and returns a prediction.
Example response:

{
  "prediction": "Suspicious",
  "confidence": 0.82,
  "reasons": [
    "High outbound network usage",
    "Background activity detected"
  ]
}

detector.py

Contains the core detection logic used by the backend.

The current prototype uses a rule-based scoring system to simulate AI-based malware detection.

Indicators currently analysed:

outbound network usage

background application activity

connections to suspicious domains

A score is calculated based on these indicators and converted into a confidence level for the prediction.

This module can later be replaced or extended with a machine learning mode

schemas.py

Defines Pydantic data models used for validating API input and output.

Request model:
AnalyzeRequest

Fields:
network_mb
background_activity
suspicious_domains_count

Response model:
AnalyzeResponse

Fields:
prediction
confidence
reasons

Using Pydantic ensures that incoming API requests are properly validated.

Installation
1. Clone the repository
git clone https://github.com/gitvihanga/ai-data-exfiltration-detector.git
cd ai-data-exfiltration-detector/backend

2. Create a virtual environment
Windows:
python -m venv .venv
.venv\Scripts\activate

Mac/Linux:
python3 -m venv .venv
source .venv/bin/activate

3. Install dependencies
pip install -r requirements.txt

Dependencies:
fastapi
uvicorn
pydantic

Running the Backend

Start the server using Uvicorn:
uvicorn app.main:app --reload

The backend will start at:
http://127.0.0.1:8000

API Documentation
FastAPI automatically generates API documentation.

Swagger UI:
http://127.0.0.1:8000/docs

ReDoc:
http://127.0.0.1:8000/redoc

These interfaces allow you to test the API endpoints directly in the browser.

Example Request

POST /analyze
Example request body:
{
  "network_mb": 75,
  "background_activity": true,
  "suspicious_domains_count": 2
}

Example response:
{
  "prediction": "Suspicious",
  "confidence": 0.85,
  "reasons": [
    "High outbound network usage",
    "Background activity detected",
    "Connection to suspicious domains"
  ]
}

Current Status

This repository represents an early backend prototype developed during the initial stages of the project.
Current functionality includes:
FastAPI backend setup
API endpoint design
behavioural analysis logic
request validation using Pydantic
automatic API documentation

Future development in the official project repository will include:
machine learning model integration
secure communication with the Android client
encrypted log storage
improved behavioural analysis
production-level architecture

